data: {"type":"response.function_call_arguments.done","arguments":"{\"title\":\"Weather Patterns in California\",\"content\":\"### General Weather Patterns\\nCalifornia's weather is diverse due to its large size and varied geography:\\n\\n- **Coastal Areas**: Typically have a Mediterranean climate with mild, wet winters and dry summers.\\n- **Inland Areas**: Experience more extreme temperatures, with hot summers and cold winters.\\n- **Mountainous Regions**: Such as the Sierra Nevada, have colder temperatures and significant snowfall in winter.\\n\\n### Seasonal Variations\\n- **Winter**: Coastal areas remain mild, while inland and mountainous regions can experience cold temperatures and snow.\\n- **Spring**: Temperatures rise, and rainfall decreases, marking a transitional period with blooming flora.\\n- **Summer**: Coastal areas stay cool due to ocean breezes, but inland areas can become very hot. Wildfires are more common during this dry season.\\n- **Fall**: Temperatures cool, and some areas may experience the Santa Ana winds, which can exacerbate fire conditions.\\n\\n### Recent Trends and Changes\\n- **Increased Temperatures**: Average temperatures have risen across the state.\\n- **Droughts**: More frequent and severe droughts have impacted water supply and agriculture.\\n- **Wildfires**: The frequency and intensity of wildfires have increased, partly due to drier conditions and higher temperatures.\\n- **Precipitation Variability**: Greater variability in precipitation, with some years experiencing heavy rainfall and others being extremely dry.\"}","item_id":"fc_047acc0521eb78230069973a1997588194975502e651f4750a","output_index":1,"sequence_number":445}

